<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-584-973  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 584 973.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 5 1990 v24 n44 p89(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Who gets custody? (departmental control over imaging systems)(Image Processing Systems Special Report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weixel, Suzanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Introducing electronic document processing into a company can leadto concerns over which department will manage the technology.andO;Will it be information systems (IS) or the individual branchesusing image processing applications.andP;  The question of control isunderlined since image processing started appearing in userenvironments rather than in data centers.andP;  A compromiserelationship, in which information systems advises and supportsthe department using the technology, is often successful.andP;  Userscan be reluctant to share managerial responsibility when thesubject matter of the records is confidential, yet IS experts needto be involved in image processing activities in order to dealwith capacity planning or interactions between an imaging systemand the corporate data base.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image processingImaging TechnologyDocument ProcessingInformation SystemsInformation Storage and Retrieval.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>